1. Default Authentication After OpenShift Installation
When an OpenShift cluster is installed, it automatically creates two administrative access methods.
1️⃣ kubeconfig File
The kubeconfig file stores cluster access credentials.
Example location:
~/.kube/config
Or admin kubeconfig:
/home/core/auth/kubeconfig
This file contains:
•	API server address
•	authentication token
•	certificates
Example structure:
clusters:
users:
contexts:
Example command
Login using kubeconfig:
oc login --kubeconfig=kubeconfig
or
export KUBECONFIG=/path/kubeconfig
Then use:
oc get nodes
________________________________________
2️⃣ kubeadmin Virtual User
OpenShift also creates a temporary user:
kubeadmin
Password stored in:
kubeadmin-password
Example login:
oc login -u kubeadmin -p <password> https://api.cluster:6443
Important rule:
kubeadmin should be removed after configuring identity providers
because it is only meant for initial cluster setup.
________________________________________
2. HTPasswd Identity Provider
HTPasswd is a simple authentication method.
Users are stored in a file like this:
username:hashed_password
Example:
developer:$apr1$abc123$asdfghjkl
Passwords are hashed, not plain text.
________________________________________
Where OpenShift Stores HTPasswd Data
OpenShift stores the htpasswd file inside a Kubernetes Secret.
Example secret:
auth-review
Namespace:
openshift-config
Check secret:
oc get secret -n openshift-config
View secret:
oc describe secret auth-review -n openshift-config
________________________________________
3. OAuth Custom Resource
Authentication configuration is stored in the OAuth cluster resource.
View it:
oc get oauth cluster -o yaml
Example configuration:
spec:
  identityProviders:
  - name: htpasswd
    type: HTPasswd
    htpasswd:
      fileData:
        name: auth-review
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
identityProviders	list of authentication providers
name	provider name
type	authentication type
fileData	secret storing htpasswd file
________________________________________
4. Managing HTPasswd Users
To change users you must:
1️⃣ Extract secret
2️⃣ Modify htpasswd file
3️⃣ Recreate secret
________________________________________
Step 1: Extract HTPasswd File
oc extract secret/auth-review \
-n openshift-config --to=.
This retrieves the htpasswd file from the secret.
________________________________________
Step 2: Modify Users
Use htpasswd command.
Add user:
htpasswd -b htpasswd newuser password
Update password:
htpasswd -b htpasswd username newpassword
Delete user:
htpasswd -D htpasswd username
________________________________________
Step 3: Update Secret
Recreate the secret:
oc create secret generic auth-review \
--from-file htpasswd=htpasswd \
-n openshift-config --dry-run=client -o yaml | oc apply -f -
Then OpenShift automatically updates authentication.
________________________________________
5. OpenShift Users and Identities
OpenShift creates two internal objects when a user logs in.
User Resource
Represents the OpenShift user.
Check users:
oc get users
Example:
developer
tester
admin
________________________________________
Identity Resource
Represents the authentication provider identity.
Check identities:
oc get identities
Example:
htpasswd:developer
ldap:user1
________________________________________
6. Deleting OpenShift Users
To fully remove a user you must remove:
1️⃣ credentials from identity provider
2️⃣ OpenShift user object
3️⃣ identity object
________________________________________
Step 1 Remove credentials
Example:
htpasswd -D htpasswd developer
________________________________________
Step 2 Delete user resource
oc delete user developer
________________________________________
Step 3 Delete identity
oc delete identity htpasswd:developer
________________________________________
7. RBAC (Role-Based Access Control)
OpenShift uses RBAC to control user permissions.
RBAC answers:
What is the user allowed to do?
RBAC consists of:
Roles
RoleBindings
ClusterRoles
ClusterRoleBindings
________________________________________
8. What is a Role?
A role is a set of permissions.
Example rule:
create pods
delete services
view deployments
Example default roles:
Role	Permission
cluster-admin	full cluster control
admin	project administration
edit	modify resources
view	read-only
________________________________________
9. Assigning Roles
Users get permissions by role bindings.
RoleBinding connects:
role → user/group
________________________________________
Assign Role to User
Example:
oc policy add-role-to-user edit developer
Meaning:
developer can modify project resources
________________________________________
Assign Role to Group
Example:
oc policy add-role-to-group edit developers
Meaning:
all users in developers group get edit permissions
________________________________________
10. Cluster-Level Roles
Cluster roles apply to the entire cluster.
Example roles:
cluster-admin
cluster-reader
self-provisioner
________________________________________
Grant Cluster Admin
Command:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin user1
Meaning:
user1 becomes cluster administrator
They can now:
create nodes
manage authentication
create projects
manage operators
________________________________________
11. Project Creation Control
By default:
all authenticated users can create projects
This happens because of role:
self-provisioner
Assigned to group:
system:authenticated:oauth
________________________________________
Remove Project Creation
Command:
oc adm policy remove-cluster-role-from-group \
self-provisioner system:authenticated:oauth
Now:
normal users cannot create projects
________________________________________
12. Grant Project Creation to Specific Group
Example:
oc adm groups new managers
Add users:
oc adm groups add-users managers leader
Give project creation permission:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-group self-provisioner managers
Now only managers group can create projects.
________________________________________
13. Final Authentication + Authorization Flow
OpenShift authentication process:
User login
     │
     ▼
OAuth Server
     │
     ▼
Identity Provider
     │
     ▼
User + Identity objects created
     │
     ▼
RBAC roles applied
     │
     ▼
User allowed to access resources
